article.description: Mwadi Mabika scored 19 points to lead the Sparks to a 73-63 victory over New York, handing the Liberty their season-high seventh straight loss.
article.headline: Sparks hand Liberty seventh straight loss
article.linkText: Sparks hand Liberty seventh straight loss
article.story:
NEW YORK -- When the New York Liberty made a run to cut Los Angeles' 17-point lead to four midway through the fourth quarter, the Sparks kept their composure and held on for a much-needed victory.

Mwadi Mabika scored 19 points to lead Los Angeles to a 73-63 win over New York on Tuesday night, giving the Sparks their second win in 12 games and stretching the Liberty's losing skid to seven.

"When they put pressure on you, you can't be afraid to accept the pressure and make smart plays under pressure and when you're fatigued," Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. "As you saw, the bottom can fall out any moment. Luckily, we held strong."

Taj McWilliams-Franklin had 13 points and 13 rebounds for her second straight double-double and Temeka Johnson and Sidney Spencer added 10 points apiece for Los Angeles (9-16).

The Sparks won despite committing 14 of their 26 turnovers in the fourth quarter

The Liberty pulled to 66-62 on Janel McCarville's layup with 4:38 left, but the Sparks closed the game with a 7-1 run over the final 2:52.

"We kept our poise, that was the difference," Mabika said. "Even though we had a lot of turnovers, we still kept our poise and made it back when it counted most."

McCarville finished with 16 points and Loree Moore had 10 for New York (10-15), which has its longest losing streak since a franchise-worst 11-game skid last season. The Liberty's previous five losses were by an average of 4.6 points.

"Our last six have been tough games," New York coach Pat Coyle said. "I can't be upset with this team. They're playing as hard as they can. We're just making young mistakes. Sooner or later, we're going to stop making them."

The Liberty remained tied with Washington for fifth place in the Eastern Conference, one game behind Chicago for the fourth and final playoff spot. The Sky lost 74-56 at Connecticut, and the Mystics lost 66-57 at Indiana.

"We are in control of what we need to do to get better, and hopefully we will take care of business," McCarville said. "We can't get too low on ourselves. We have to go right back out, ready to work hard the next day."

After Cathrine Kraayeveld's layup pulled New York to 51-42, Los Angeles scored eight straight points to stretch the lead to 17 with 1:22 left in the third quarter. Mabika had a 3-pointer and Marta Fernandez and Spencer added driving layups during the run.

New York then used a 13-2 spurt to pull to 61-55 with 8:23 left in the game. McCarville started the run with a jumper with 15 seconds to go in the third quarter and Lisa Willis, acquired from Los Angeles on June 20, hit a 3 to open the fourth.

The Liberty then scored eight straight points in 34 seconds as Ashley Battle made a 3, Willis hit another and stole the ensuing inbounds pass and had a layup.

"We put ourselves in a great position to actually come back," Moore said. "We got the turnovers and momentum we needed, but we just couldn't finish it the way we wanted to."

The Sparks finished with a 56-36 edged in rebounding and had 12 of their 16 offensive rebounds in the first half.

"The second quarter was brutal," Coyle said. "We gave them too many second shots. Our initial D was good. When you get three, four looks at the basket, you're bound to hit a quarter of them."

Los Angeles opened the second quarter with a 12-0 run to take a 26-23 lead on McWilliams-Franklin's free throw with 6:27 left. McCarville snapped the Liberty's scoring drought with a jumper 19 seconds later.

The Sparks scored five straight points, capped by Johnson's jumper, to take a six-point lead with 5:04 remaining in the half.

After Moore's jumper pulled New York to 32-29, McWilliams-Franklin hit a jumper and a 3-pointer to push Los Angeles' lead to eight. Murriel Page's running jumper with 34 seconds left gave the Sparks a 41-31 lead at the half.
